      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In cases of Vitamin B12 deficiency, it's not just a matter of not consuming enough B12. The issue is often a combination of both inadequate intake and impaired absorption.\n\nWhen intrinsic factor is low or absent, the Vitamin B12-intrinsic factor complex cannot form, and the Vitamin B12 is not absorbed into the bloodstream. Even if the body is consuming sufficient amounts of Vitamin B12, it may not be able to absorb it effectively.\n\nIn some cases, Vitamin B12 can be lost or \"missing\" from the system due to other factors, such as:\n\n* Malabsorption: Certain conditions, like celiac disease or Crohn's disease, can damage the small intestine and impair Vitamin B12 absorption.\n* Increased requirements: Pregnant or breastfeeding women, for example, may require more Vitamin B12 due to increased demands on the body.\n* Increased excretion: Certain medications, such as proton pump inhibitors, can increase the excretion of Vitamin B12 in the urine.\n\nSo, it's not just a matter of not eating enough B12-rich foods or not getting enough B12 supplements. The body's ability to absorb and retain Vitamin B12 is also crucial, and any issues with intrinsic factor or the stomach lining can impair this",
